      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Albuterol (Proventil, Ventolin) 2.5 mg Nebulizer</strong></td>
          <td>Short-acting beta-2 agonist (SABA) — Rescue bronchodilator</td>
          <td>Onset 5–15 min; stimulates beta-2 receptors → bronchodilation; monitor HR (tachycardia), tremor, hypokalemia; use for acute bronchospasm; reassess lung sounds and SpO2 after each treatment; notify provider if no response after 3 treatments</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Prednisone (Deltasone) PO</strong></td>
          <td>Systemic corticosteroid</td>
          <td>Inhibits inflammatory mediators; reduces airway edema and mucus production; monitor blood glucose (hyperglycemia), BP, fluid retention, mood; administer with food; short course does not require tapering; do not abruptly stop long-term corticosteroids</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Normal Saline 0.9% IV — 125 mL/hr</strong></td>
          <td>Isotonic crystalloid IV fluid</td>
          <td>Hydration support — thins mucus secretions; maintains vascular volume; monitor IV site, I&amp;O, lung sounds for fluid overload; ensure correct flow rate per order</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Oxygen via Non-Rebreather Mask (NRB)</strong></td>
          <td>Supportive — O2 delivery device</td>
          <td>Set at 10–15 LPM; inflate reservoir bag before placing on patient; bag must not fully collapse during inspiration (increase flow if it does); delivers 60–90% FiO2; monitor SpO2 continuously; target ≥92% in asthma (unlike COPD, do not restrict O2 in asthma); reassess mask fit frequently</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
