    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: Define asthma and describe its common triggers.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Asthma</strong> is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways characterized by airway inflammation, bronchospasm, increased mucus production, and airway hyperresponsiveness. The resulting airflow obstruction is typically <strong>reversible</strong> — distinguishing it from COPD.</p>
        <p><strong>Common Triggers:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Respiratory infections (pneumonia, URI — Kimberly's trigger)</li>
          <li>Allergens: dust mites, pollen, pet dander, mold</li>
          <li>Exercise (exercise-induced bronchoconstriction)</li>
          <li>Cold air, dry air</li>
          <li>Tobacco smoke and air pollution</li>
          <li>NSAID/aspirin use (aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease)</li>
          <li>Emotional stress and anxiety</li>
          <li>Occupational exposures (chemicals, dust, fumes)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: How does anxiety worsen an asthma exacerbation, and what nursing interventions address it?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Anxiety–Asthma Link:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Anxiety activates the sympathetic nervous system → increased RR → hyperventilation → worsens air trapping and V/Q mismatch</li>
          <li>Anxiety-driven hyperventilation paradoxically worsens gas exchange in an already-obstructed airway</li>
          <li>Creates a feedback loop: dyspnea → fear → worse dyspnea</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Nursing Interventions:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Remain calm and present — do not leave the room</li>
          <li>Use a therapeutic, reassuring tone — "You're in the right place. The medication is working."</li>
          <li>Breathing coaching — "Follow my lead — breathe in slowly, breathe out slowly"</li>
          <li>Reduce environmental stimulation — dim lights, lower noise level if possible</li>
          <li>Give simple, one-at-a-time instructions — do not overwhelm</li>
          <li>Administer ordered bronchodilators promptly — improving breathing reduces anxiety</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Describe the correct application and monitoring of a non-rebreather mask.</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Correct NRB Application:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Set flow rate to 10–15 LPM</li>
          <li><strong>Inflate the reservoir bag before placing on the patient</strong> — occlude the bag's valve and allow it to fill fully</li>
          <li>Place mask over nose and mouth; mold the nose piece for a seal</li>
          <li>Adjust elastic straps so mask fits snugly without causing pressure injury</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Ongoing Monitoring:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reservoir bag should deflate slightly during inhalation and re-inflate during exhalation</li>
          <li>If the bag fully collapses: immediately increase flow rate — patient may be rebreathing CO2</li>
          <li>Monitor SpO2 continuously — document response to O2 therapy</li>
          <li>Check mask seal — if patient is mouth-breathing around the mask, adjust fit</li>
          <li>Reassess skin under the mask for pressure injury with prolonged use</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: Why does prednisone cause hyperglycemia, and which patients are most at risk?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Mechanism of Steroid-Induced Hyperglycemia:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Corticosteroids stimulate gluconeogenesis in the liver → increased glucose production</li>
          <li>Reduce peripheral glucose uptake by decreasing insulin receptor sensitivity (insulin resistance)</li>
          <li>May also reduce pancreatic insulin secretion in susceptible individuals</li>
          <li>The effect is dose-dependent and peaks approximately 4–8 hours after oral administration</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Patients Most at Risk:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Known diabetics (Type 1 or Type 2) — require insulin adjustments during steroid course</li>
          <li>Prediabetics — may present with overt diabetes for the first time</li>
          <li>Patients with strong family history of diabetes</li>
          <li>Obese patients — already insulin resistant</li>
          <li>Even previously normoglycemic patients like Kimberly can develop transient hyperglycemia on steroids</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What are the key discharge education topics for Kimberly regarding asthma management?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Asthma Action Plan:</strong> Review green/yellow/red zones; know when to use rescue inhaler, call the provider, or call 911</li>
          <li><strong>Rescue vs. Controller inhalers:</strong> Albuterol is rescue (for acute symptoms); maintenance/controller inhalers (inhaled corticosteroids) prevent exacerbations — never use rescue inhaler as a substitute for controller</li>
          <li><strong>Inhaler technique:</strong> Shake, exhale, slow deep inhalation, hold breath 10 seconds; use a spacer for better delivery</li>
          <li><strong>Identify and avoid triggers:</strong> Keep an asthma diary; respiratory infections are a major trigger — annual flu vaccine, pneumococcal vaccine</li>
          <li><strong>Peak flow monitoring:</strong> Use a peak flow meter daily; recognize personal best and action zones</li>
          <li><strong>Follow-up:</strong> Schedule appointment with primary provider or pulmonologist within 1–2 weeks; do not wait until next exacerbation</li>
          <li><strong>When to seek emergency care:</strong> If rescue inhaler provides no relief; if unable to speak in sentences; if lips or fingertips turn blue</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

